					<p>The article is devoted to the struggles undertaken in the cinema of the last few decades to portray the events and memories of left-wing terrorism in Europe in the 1970s. The main object of interest are two national contexts: that of Germany and that of Italy. Both of these traditions have addressed the events of the era in an especially multilayered manner. The article provides not only the general panorama of social and political transformations but also interpretations of numerous films from 1970s onwards.</p>
